post_cb({"2985634": {"ParentId": "2985622", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<pre><code>wchar_t *file = L\"C:/x.bmp\";\n</code></pre>\n<p>L introduces a wide string.</p>\n<p>In Windows, it's customary to use macros that behave differently according to some preprocessor definitions. See <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/c426s321(VS.71).aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/c426s321(VS.71).aspx</a></p>\n<p>You would write:</p>\n<pre><code>_TCHAR *file = _TEXT(\"C:/x.bmp\");\n</code></pre>\n", "OwnerUserId": "127724", "LastEditorUserId": "151292", "LastEditDate": "2010-06-06T19:51:26.357", "Id": "2985634", "Score": "8", "CreationDate": "2010-06-06T19:40:29.540", "LastActivityDate": "2010-06-06T19:51:26.357"}, "2985622": {"CommentCount": "5", "ViewCount": "1477", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "131926", "CreationDate": "2010-06-06T19:38:35.413", "LastActivityDate": "2010-06-06T19:51:26.357", "Title": "Making use of WCHAR as a CHAR?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "2985634", "LastEditDate": "2010-06-06T19:41:58.103", "Id": "2985622", "Score": "1", "Body": "<p>GDI+ makes use of WCHAR instead of what the WinAPI allows which is CHAR. Usually I can do: </p>\n<pre><code>char *str = \"C:/x.bmp\";\n</code></pre>\n<p>but how do I do this for wchar? I can't juse do</p>\n<pre><code>wchar_t *file = \"C:/x.bmp\";\n</code></pre>\n<p>Thanks</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c>", "OwnerUserId": "146780", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "2985635": {"ParentId": "2985622", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<pre><code>const wchar_t *file = L\"C:/x.bmp\";\n</code></pre>\n<p>This is according to C++ Standard 2.13.4/1:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_2985622_2985635_0\">&lt;...&gt;A string literal that begins with L,\n  such as L\"asdf\", is a wide string\n  literal. A wide string literal has type \u201carray of n const wchar_t\u201d and has static storage duration, where\n     n is the size of the string as defined below, and is initialized with the given characters.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Note that you should use <code>const</code> qualifier here. The effect of attempting to modify a string literal is undefined (2.13.4/2).</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "123111", "LastEditorUserId": "123111", "LastEditDate": "2010-06-06T19:48:18.757", "Id": "2985635", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2010-06-06T19:40:35.423", "LastActivityDate": "2010-06-06T19:48:18.757"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_2985622_2985635_0": {"section_id": 5360, "quality": 0.8846153846153846, "length": 23}}, "n3337": {"so_2985622_2985635_0": {"section_id": 5156, "quality": 0.8846153846153846, "length": 23}}, "n4659": {"so_2985622_2985635_0": {"section_id": 6785, "quality": 0.7692307692307693, "length": 20}}}});